snippet.textDisplay: Fun Fact #3: The "[blank] US Gallons" on the fuel cap is another aircraft thing. US FAA regulations starting around the 70's or 80's required all fuel caps to be labelled with the type of fuel that the airplane used, and the # of gallons it could take.  This came about after a few propeller airplanes accidentally got jet fuel put into their tanks (with the same kind of results you'd expect if you threw diesel into your gasoline car).

Fun fact: those "Reset" buttons (@18:16) are Circuit Breakers (instead of Fuses). And yes, they're the same type used in aircraft. :-P

snippet.textDisplay: OMG!!!!  A speedometer that updates in real time?  And mirrors that are controlled by switches!!!  Please, Doug, you are not in high school.  I know you are a bit giddy being so close to a W8 but there is nothing "insane" or "crazy" about this car.  It doesn't look that far from the Countach of the same era.  There were certainly a few odd design choices, such as the gear selector between the door and driver's seat, but it was done for a reason.  To know why would be interesting.  The body styling is just that; styling.  The W8 is certainly not as "crazy" as the AM Lagonda in that realm.  The body shell was designed to suit the chassis and engine packaging and reduced to it's minimum capacity.  To dress that up and give the car it's own look, the slats were added.  For a car such as the W8 you should have tracked down some of the designers or design documents to give us better insight on what made the W8 the W8 not just repeat "insane" and "crazy" at every little detail.  My apologies if you take this criticism as being harsh but in today's age we are losing the intelligence of information and instead are being spoon-fed titillation and false drama as if we are children.  I was looking forward to this review but after the sixth bout of "insane" and "crazy" I couldn't see it through.
